  "prompt": "How did the saying, \"goodnight Vienna\" originate?",
  "response": "The saying \"goodnight Vienna\" is a British phrase that typically means something is finished or over, often with a connotation of defeat or termination. Its origin is a bit unclear, but it's generally believed to have come into popular use after World War II.\n\nOne possible source of the phrase is the title of a 1932 British film and musical called \"Goodnight, Vienna,\" which was quite popular at the time. The film featured a romantic storyline set in Vienna, and the title song, \"Goodnight, Vienna,\" was performed in the production. The catchy nature of the song and the film's popularity may have contributed to the phrase entering the British vernacular.\n\nOver time, the phrase evolved in meaning, losing its romantic connotations and instead being used in contexts where something is effectively over or someone's prospects have declined significantly. While it's difficult to pinpoint the exact reason for this shift in usage, it's not uncommon for cultural references to transform and take on new meanings as they become more widely adopted in everyday language.",
